'''Sigismondo Polcastro''' (1384–1473) was an Italian [[physician]] and [[natural philosopher]]. He was born to a jurist father, Girolamo, of the ancient de&nbsp;Porcastris family of [[Vicenza]], and Maddalena Volpe of [[Padua]]. Perhaps born in Vicenza, he moved to Padua while he was still a boy.<ref name=Italian_encyclopedia />
He received a doctorate in arts from the [[University of Padua]] in 1412, taught natural philosophy from 1419, obtained a doctorate in medicine in 1424, and taught medicine from 1426 to 1464 or 1465. He wrote several short medical works.<ref name=Italian_encyclopedia>[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/sigismondo-polcastro_(Dizionario-Biografico)/ "POLCASTRO, Sigismondo" – article in the Italian Encyclopaedia of Science, Letters, and Arts] (in Italian)</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5hTHP2I-A14C&pg=PA24 |title=The Universities of the Italian Renaissance |author=Paul F. Grendler |publisher=JHU Press |year=2002 |pages=24–25 |isbn=0801866316 }}</ref>
In 2016, he was pronounced the progenitor of the largest group of mathematicians in the [[Mathematics Genealogy Project]], which groups mathematicians by teacher–student mentoring relationships,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.nature.com/news/majority-of-mathematicians-hail-from-just-24-scientific-families-1.20491 |title=Majority of mathematicians hail from just 24 scientific ‘families’ |author=Davide Castelvecchi |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume=537 |pages=20–21 |year=2016 |doi=10.1038/nature.2016.20491 |pmid=27582203}}</ref> via his student [[Pietro Roccabonella]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=164338 |title=Sigismondo Polcastro |publisher=[[Mathematics Genealogy Project]] |accessdate=30 September 2016 }}</ref>
